{"title":"Pretty ggplot2 correlation matrices","markdown":{"yaml":{"title":"Pretty ggplot2 correlation matrices","description":"Example code for creating custom ggplot2 correlation matrices","author":"Giacomo Bignardi","date":"5/22/2021","draft":true},"headingText":"Making nice correlation plots in ggplot2","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n\n\nA correlation matrix is the backbone of a lot of statistical methods. Therefore, having nice ways to present correlation matrices in papers is quite handy.\n\nEven though there are a few great R packages for creating correlation matrix plots, creating them directly in ggplot2 allows a lot more flexibility.\n\nA nice property of Pearson's correlation coefficient is that you all only need two pieces of informatjion\n\n```{r}\n\ndata(mtcars)\n\nhead(mtcars)\n\ndf = mtcars\n\ncor(mtcars)\n```\n\n## Standard approach\n\n```{r}\ncorrplot::corrplot(cor(df), addCoef.col = 'black')\n\n```\n\n## Ggplot\n\n```{r}\n\ngbtoolbox::plot_correlations(df)\n```\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\n\n# Making nice correlation plots in ggplot2\n\nA correlation matrix is the backbone of a lot of statistical methods. Therefore, having nice ways to present correlation matrices in papers is quite handy.\n\nEven though there are a few great R packages for creating correlation matrix plots, creating them directly in ggplot2 allows a lot more flexibility.\n\nA nice property of Pearson's correlation coefficient is that you all only need two pieces of informatjion\n\n```{r}\n\ndata(mtcars)\n\nhead(mtcars)\n\ndf = mtcars\n\ncor(mtcars)\n```\n\n## Standard approach\n\n```{r}\ncorrplot::corrplot(cor(df), addCoef.col = 'black')\n\n```\n\n## Ggplot\n\n```{r}\n\ngbtoolbox::plot_correlations(df)\n```\n"},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":true,"echo":true,"output":tr